The paper deals with mechanism design, which is a subfield of game theory (cs.GT). It also involves algorithms and computational complexity (cs.DS), as the authors discuss the runtime of their proposed mechanisms. The use of Bayesian mechanisms and the consideration of bidder-symmetric and item-symmetric distributions suggest a connection to artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also deals with economic concepts such as demand constraints and revenue, indicating a connection to computational economics (cs.EC). Finally, the authors mention a technique for turning an eps-BIC mechanism into a truly-BIC mechanism, which involves information theory (cs.IT).
